A global restaurant menu aggregation system requires a scalable, microservices-based architecture to ingest, normalize, and serve menu data across multiple countries, languages, and currencies. Core components include a web scraper/API connector, a data normalization service, a geo-distributed NoSQL database, and an API gateway that handles menu localization for end-users. [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
## Key Architectural Components

* Ingestion Service (Scraper/API Connector): Handles asynchronous ingestion from diverse restaurant POS systems and web sources,, which is often done via [custom web scraping and data aggregation systems](https://hightechgrowth.com/case-studies/menuportal_case_study.pdf) to manage thousands of restaurants.
* Normalization & Cleaning Service: Converts disparate menu formats, languages, and pricing structures into a unified schema, utilizing AI to map items and prices.
* Storage (Database): A NoSQL database (e.g., Cassandra) is used to manage massive, highly available, and regionally partitioned menu data.
* Menu Aggregation Service: A central service that manages menu updates, ensuring a single, accurate point of truth for [enterprise menu management](https://lunchbox.io/learn/solving-menu-management-for-enterprise-restaurants).
* API Gateway & Localization: Delivers localized content, applying currency conversion and language translation based on user location. [1, 2, 3, 4, 6]

## System Design Considerations

* Scalability: The system must handle high read traffic, requiring multiple read replicas and regional data centers.
* Consistency: Use a [multi-tenant platform](https://www.abbacustechnologies.com/how-to-build-a-multi-tenant-digital-restaurant-menu-platform-with-qr-code-access/) to ensure that updates in one location are propagated across all channels (web, apps) in real-time.
* Data Aggregation: Leverage a centralized menu management system to aggregate and edit menus across 3rd party platforms. [1, 3, 7, 8]

## Data Flow

   1. Ingestion: Raw menu data is collected from APIs or via specialized scrapers, as highlighted in this case study.
   2. Processing: Data is normalized, translated, and assigned a regional currency.
   3. Storage: Data is written to a distributed database.
   4. Serving: The frontend requests data from the API, which serves localized data. [1, 3, 4]

## Technologies

* Database: Cassandra, DynamoDB, MongoDB.
* Message Queue: Kafka (for asynchronous updates).
* Infrastructure: Kubernetes (for microservices orchestration), CDN. [3, 4, 9]


